"1335–3 January 1430":"1335–3. januar 1430","1335–1430":"1335–1430","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1365–1430":"1365–1430","1304–1355":"1304–1355","1308–1369":"1308–1369","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","3 January 1430":"3. januar 1430","1304":"1304","1337":"1337","1369":"1369","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1365":"1365","about 1369":"omkring 1369","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1308":"1308","Ardleigh, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Ardleigh, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Ardleigh, Essex, England":"Ardleigh, Essex, England","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, England"},"nl":{"1335–3 January 1430":"1335–3 januari 1430","1335–1430":"1335–1430","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1365–1430":"1365–1430","1304–1355":"1304–1355","1308–1369":"1308–1369","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","3 January 1430":"3 januari 1430","1304":"1304","1337":"1337","1369":"1369","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1365":"1365","about 1369":"circa 1369","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1308":"1308","Ardleigh, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Ardleigh, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ardleigh, Essex, England":"Ardleigh, Essex, England","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, England"},"en":{"1335–3 January 1430":"1335–3 January 1430","1335–1430":"1335–1430","1337–1380":"1337–1380","1365–1430":"1365–1430","1304–1355":"1304–1355","1308–1369":"1308–1369","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","3 January 1430":"3 January 1430","1304":"1304","1337":"1337","1369":"1369","1335":"1335","1355":"1355","1365":"1365","about 1369":"about 1369","1453":"1453","1430":"1430","1308":"1308","Ardleigh, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Ardleigh, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Ardleigh, Essex, England":"Ardleigh, Essex, England","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone, rock’ (Old English <i>stān</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on stony ground, by a notable outcrop of rock, or by a stone boundary-marker or monument, or habitational, from a place called Stone, such as those in Buckinghamshire, Devon, Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Somerset, Staffordshire, and Worcestershire.","Irish (Kilkenny): adopted for Irish <b>Ó Clochartaigh</b> (see   Clougherty  ) and/or <b>Ó Clochasaigh</b> (see   Clohessy  ), and possibly several other names containing or thought to contain the element <i>cloch</i> ‘stone’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of various surnames in other languages, meaning ‘stone’, including Jewish   Stein  , Norwegian <b>Steine</b>, French   Lapierre  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stoner","meanings":["English (Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone’ + <i>-er</i>, used for someone who lived by a prominent rock or stone, or perhaps who came from a place called Stone, although this formation is more rare. See   Stone   and compare   Stoneman  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Steiner  ."]},{"name":"Stones","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Stone   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. A number of the places called Stone are sometimes recorded with plural spellings in the medieval period, including Stone (Staffordshire), recorded as <i>Stanes</i> in 1187."]},{"name":"Stenner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt.","German: occupational name for a stonemason or stonecutter, or a topographic name for someone who lived on stony ground, from a derivative of Middle High German <i>stein</i> ‘stone’, ‘stony place’. Compare   Stone   and   Stein  .","English: variant of   Stayner  ."]},{"name":"Clougherty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aileen.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Clochartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Clochartach</i>’, a personal name, probably formed with <i>cloch</i> ‘stone’,   Stone   being an alternative Anglicized form of the surname."]},{"name":"Roach","meanings":["English:","of Norman origin, from Old French and Middle English <i>roche</i> ‘rock, cliff, promontory’, sometimes a translation of   Stone  . The surname may have been topographic, denoting someone who lived on or by a prominent rock or rocky place, or a habitational name for someone who lived or came from a place so named, such as one of those called Roque or Roche(s) in Normandy and neighboring regions, or Roche in Cornwall, Roach Farm in Clyst Hydon (Devon), or Roch in Pembrokeshire (see   Roch  ).","in Lancashire perhaps referring to the River Roch, which runs through Rochdale; the river name is probably a back-formation from <i>Recedham</i>, an early name for Rochdale recorded in 1086, derived from Old English <i>reced</i> ‘building, house, hall’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’. Alternatively, the Lancashire name could be a shortened form of the now rare or extinct surname <b>Rochdale</b> alias <b>Rachedale</b>, <i>Rachdall</i>, a habitational name from Rochdale (Lancashire). From the 18th century onward the name is difficult to distinguish from   Roch  , borne by Irish migrants to South Lancashire, especially Liverpool."]},{"name":"Stoneman","meanings":["English: perhaps an occupational name for someone who was the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of a person surnamed   Stone  . Alternatively, the name may have been an alias of   Stone  , used for someone who lived by a prominent stone or rock or at a minor place so named (Middle English <i>ston</i> + <i>man</i>).","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name for someone who worked with stone or who sold precious stones; a jeweler.","English: perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Ston(e)man</i> (Old English <i>Stān(e)mann</i>), a pet form of Old English personal names beginning with <i>Stān-</i> (from the word ‘stone’, ‘rock’) + the Old English hypocoristic suffix <i>-mann</i>."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"Atte","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which was derived in the medieval period from the Old English personal name <i>Tāta</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Atte Stone was born in 1335, in Ardleigh, Essex, England, his father, John Atte Stone, was 31 and his mother, Elizabeth Empson, was 27. He had at least 2 sons with Unknown Unknown. He died on 3 January 1430, in his hometown, at the age of 95."},"et":{"1335–3 January 1430":"1335–3. jaanuar 1430","133